{
  "text": "whose expected value can be written as a rank-one matrix. We refer to η = 1 − p as the noise level in the data. Following the approach used in [CITATION_1] and using recent results on the largest eigenvalue of rank-one deformation matrices, one can give a similar analysis for the robustness to noise of the eigenvalue method for synchronization over Z 2 (see Appendix A), by decomposing the given matrix Z into a sum of a rank-one matrix and a random matrix R corresponding to the noise in the measurement graph. In Figure 4 .1, we show histograms of the eigenvalues of the measurement matrix Z of size n = 1000 for the complete graph case (thus α = 1), as well as the resulting error levels τ , for different values of the noise level p in the data. The additional numerical simulations shown in original matrix Z of pairwise measurements, as we vary the edge probability α on the x-axis, and the noise level p on the y-axis. The intensity of the color denotes the error level τ , with dark blue indicating a perfect recovery, and dark red indicating an erroneous solution that is very close to random. We measure accuracy by the percentage of nodes correctly classified. On the right plot of the same Figure 4 .2, we plot the spectral gap λ",
